:"1173","about 1110":"circa 1110","Tavistock, Devon, England":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Waldexote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1110–1173":"about 1110–1173","1110–1173":"1110–1173","1116–Female":"1116–Deceased","1140–1166":"1140–1166","1065–1173":"1065–1173","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1080":"1080","1116":"1116","1137":"1137","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","about 1110":"about 1110","Tavistock, Devon, England":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Waldexote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Molis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Lithuanian: occupational name from <i>molius</i> ‘brickmaker’ or <i>molis</i> ‘clay’, also used in a transferred senses as a nickname for a dirty person. This surname is also found in Poland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas de Molis was born about 1110, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Meulles, was 47 and his mother, Lady Roger de FitzBaldwin, was 32. He married Mrs. Nicholas De Moels in 1137, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1173, in England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"about 1110–1173":"umbes 1110–1173","1110–1173":"1110–1173","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1140–1166":"1140–1166","1065–1173":"1065–1173","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1116":"1116","1137":"1137","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","about 1110":"umbes 1110","Tavistock, Devon, England":"Tavistock, Devon, England","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Waldexote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingd